# Go Style (Effective Go)

Follow [Effective Go](https://go.dev/doc/effective_go) and standard Go tooling.

## Formatting

- Run `gofmt` (or `go fmt ./...`) on all changed Go files before handing off.
- Use `goimports` when available to manage imports.

## Structure

- Short, focused functions with clear names (`CamelCase` exported, `camelCase` unexported).
- Keep `main` in `app/main.go`; put logic in other files or subpackages under `app/`.
- One package per directory; avoid stashing unrelated helpers in `main`.
- Accept interfaces, return concrete types where practical.

## Errors and APIs

- Check errors; do not ignore `_` unless intentional and obvious.
- Return errors rather than panicking for expected failure paths.
- Document exported identifiers with concise comments starting with the name.

## Naming and literals

- Prefer `i` for short loops; meaningful names for longer scopes.
- Use mixed caps for acronyms consistently (`HTTPServer`, not `HttpServer`).

## Example layout

```
app/
  main.go          # REPL loop, delegates to shell package
  shell/
    shell.go       # Shell type and Run method
    builtins.go    # builtin command handlers
```
